    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "Do NOT use distributed locks (Redis/Redlock) for the double-assignment problem — PostgreSQL row locks are simpler and more correct for a 2-person team",
      "Do NOT use eventual consistency for assignment state — the double-assignment invariant requires strong consistency at the point of assignment",
      "Do NOT split into microservices — a 2-person team cannot operate multiple services effectively. Keep it as one deployable unit.",
      "Do NOT use SELECT FOR UPDATE without SKIP LOCKED — without it, concurrent assignments will serialize and blow past the 200ms latency target",
      "Do NOT cache assignment decisions — only cache candidate pre-filtering data. The assignment itself must always go through the DB."
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [
    {
      "type": "contradictory_requirements",
      "description": "Requirements 2 (strong consistency: no double-assignment) and 3 (high availability during DB node failure) are in direct tension per the CAP theorem. During a database failover window, the system CANNOT guarantee both simultaneously. The product team must decide: during the brief failover window (5-30 seconds), should the system (A) reject/queue assignment requests to preserve consistency, or (B) allow assignments with a small risk of double-assignment that gets resolved after the fact?",
